# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bullet-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bullet-physics/bullet-software] The Bullet physics library is free and open-source software subject to the terms of the zlib License.
[src:bullet-physics/bullet-software] The source code is hosted on GitHub; before 2014 it was hosted on Google Code.
[src:bullet-physics/bullet-software] The Bullet website also hosts a Physics Forum for general discussion around physics simulation for games and animation.
[src:bullet-physics/bullet-software] At AMD Developer Summit (APU) in November 2013 Erwin Coumans presented the Bullet 3 OpenCL Rigid Body Simulation.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Collision detection is closely linked to calculating the distance between objects, as objects collide when the distance between them is less than or equal to zero.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Negative distances indicate that one object has penetrated another.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Performing collision detection requires more context than just the distance between the objects.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Accurately identifying the points of contact on both objects' surfaces is also essential for computing a physically accurate collision response.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The complexity of this task increases with the level of detail in the objects' representations: the more intricate the model, the greater the computational cost.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Collision detection frequently involves dynamic objects, adding a temporal dimension to distance calculations.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Instead of simply measuring distance between static objects, collision detection algorithms often aim to determine whether the objects' motion will bring them to a point in time when their distance is zero—an operation that adds significant computational overhead.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In collision detection involving multiple objects, a naive approach would require detecting collisions for all pairwise combinations of objects.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] As the number of objects increases, the number of required comparisons grows rapidly: for n objects, ${n(n-1)}/{2}$ intersection tests are needed with a naive approach.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] This quadratic growth makes such an approach computationally expensive as n increases.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Due to the complexity mentioned above, collision detection is a computationally intensive process.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Nevertheless, it is essential for interactive applications like video games, robotics, and real-time physics engines.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] To manage these computational demands, extensive efforts have gone into optimizing collision detection algorithms.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] A commonly used approach towards accelerating the required computations is to divide the process into two phases: the **broad phase** and the **narrow phase**.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The broad phase aims to answer the question of whether objects might collide, using a conservative but efficient approach to rule out pairs that clearly do not intersect, thus avoiding unnecessary calculations.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Objects that cannot be definitively separated in the broad phase are passed to the narrow phase.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Here, more precise algorithms determine whether these objects actually intersect.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] If they do, the narrow phase often calculates the exact time and location of the intersection.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] This phase aims at quickly finding objects or parts of objects for which it can be quickly determined that no further collision test is needed.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] A useful property of such approach is that it is output sensitive.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In the context of collision detection this means that the time complexity of the collision detection is proportional to the number of objects that are close to each other.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] An early example of that is the I-COLLIDE where the number of required narrow phase collision tests was $O(n+m)$ where n is the number of objects and m is the number of objects at close proximity.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] This is a significant improvement over the quadratic complexity of the naive approach.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Several approaches can be grouped under the spatial partitioning umbrella, which includes octrees (for 3D), quadtrees (for 2D), binary space partitioning (or BSP trees) and other, similar approaches.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] If one splits space into a number of simple cells, and if two objects can be shown not to be in the same cell, then they need not be checked for intersection.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Dynamic scenes and deformable objects require updating the partitioning which can add overhead.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Bounding Volume Hierarchy (BVH) is a tree structure over a set of bounding volumes.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Collision is determined by doing a tree traversal starting from the root.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] If the bounding volume of the root doesn't intersect with the object of interest, the traversal can be stopped.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] If, however there is an intersection, the traversal proceeds and checks the branches for each there is an intersection.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Branches for which there is no intersection with the bounding volume can be culled from further intersection test.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Therefore, multiple objects can be determined to not intersect at once.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] BVH can be used with deformable objects such as cloth or soft-bodies but the volume hierarchy has to be adjusted as the shape deforms.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] For deformable objects we need to be concerned about self-collisions or self intersections.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Collision between two objects is computed by computing intersection between the bounding volumes of the root of the tree as there are collision we dive into the sub-trees that intersect.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Exact collisions between the actual objects, or its parts (often triangles of a triangle mesh) need to be computed only between intersecting leaves.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The same approach works for pair wise collision and self-collisions.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] During the broad-phase, when the objects in the world move or deform, the data-structures used to cull collisions have to be updated.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In cases where the changes between two frames or time-steps are small and the objects can be approximated well with axis-aligned bounding boxes, the sweep and prune algorithm can be a suitable approach.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The algorithm keeps track of currently intersecting boxes, and as objects move, re-sorting the intervals helps keep track of the status.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Once a pair of physical bodies has been selected for further investigation, collisions need to be checked more carefully.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] However, in many applications, individual objects (if they are not too deformable) are described by a set of smaller primitives, mainly triangles.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The obvious thing to do is to check all triangles $S_{j}$ against all triangles $T_{k}$ for collisions, but this involves $n^{2}$ comparisons, which is highly inefficient.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] If possible, it is desirable to use a pruning algorithm to reduce the number of pairs of triangles that need to be checked.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The most widely used family of algorithms is known as the *hierarchical bounding volumes* method.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] As a preprocessing step, for each object (e.g., S and T ) calculates a hierarchy of bounding volumes.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Then, at each time step, when collisions need to be checked between S and T , the hierarchical bounding volumes are used to reduce the number of pairs of triangles under consideration.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] For simplicity, provide an example using bounding spheres, although it has been noted that spheres are undesirable in many cases.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] If E is a set of triangles, a bounding sphere is pre-calculated. $B(E)$ .
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] There are many ways of choosing $B(E)$ , $B(E)$ is a sphere that completely contains E and is as small as possible.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Ahead of time, $B(S)$ and $B(T)$ can be computed.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Clearly, if these two spheres do not intersect (and that is very easy to test), then neither do S and T .
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] This is not much better than an *n*-body pruning algorithm, however.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Apply this to S and T , and calculate (ahead of time) the bounding spheres $B(L(S)),B(R(S))$ and $B(L(T)),B(R(T))$ .
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The hope here is that these bounding spheres are much smaller than $B(S)$ and $B(T)$ .
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] And, if, for instance, $B(S)$ and $B(L(T))$ do not intersect, then there is no sense in checking any triangle in S against any triangle in $L(T)$ .
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] As a precomputation, take each physical body (represented by a set of triangles) and recursively decompose it into a binary tree, where each node N represents a set of triangles, and its two children represent $L(N)$ and $R(N)$ .
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] At each node in the tree, pre-compute the bounding sphere $B(N)$ .
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] When the time comes for testing a pair of objects for collision, their bounding sphere tree can be used to eliminate many pairs of triangles.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Many variants of the algorithms are obtained by choosing something other than a sphere for $B(T)$ .
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] If one chooses axis-aligned bounding boxes, one gets AABBTrees.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Oriented bounding box trees are called OBBTrees.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Some trees are easier to update if the underlying object changes.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Some trees can accommodate higher order primitives such as splines instead of simple triangles.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In this phase, the objects under consideration are relatively close to each other.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Still, attempts to quickly determine if a full intersection is needed are employed first.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] This step is sometimes referred to as mid-phase.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Once these tests passed (e.g. the pair of objects may be colliding) more precise algorithms determine whether these objects actually intersect.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Since checking whether two objects intersect can be a relatively expensive operation, one quick way to potentially avoid the computation is to check whether the bounding volumes enclosing the two objects intersect.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Bounding volumes are typically used in the early (pruning) stage of collision detection, so that only objects with overlapping volumes need be compared in detail.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] If they don't overlap, there is no need to check the actual objects.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] A false positive intersection in this case means that the bounding volumes intersect but the actual objects do not.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Different bounding volume types offer different trade-offs for these properties.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Axis-Align Bounding Boxes (AABB) and cuboids are popular due to their simplicity and quick intersection tests.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Bounding volumes such as Oriented Bounding Boxes (OBB), K-DOPs and Convex-hulls offer a tighter approximation of the enclosed shape at the expense of a more elaborate intersection test.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Objects for which pruning approaches could not rule out the possibility of a collision have to undergo an exact collision detection computation.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] According to the separating planes theorem, for any two disjoint convex objects, there exists a plane so that one object lies completely on one side of that plane, and the other object lies on the opposite side of that plane.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] This property allows the development of efficient collision detection algorithms between convex objects.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Several algorithms are available for finding the closest points on the surface of two convex polyhedral objects - and determining collision.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Lin that used a variation on the simplex algorithm from linear programming and the Gilbert-Johnson-Keerthi distance algorithm are two such examples.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] These algorithms approach constant time when applied repeatedly to pairs of stationary or slow-moving objects, and every step is initialized from the previous collision check.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The result of all this algorithmic work is that collision detection can be done efficiently for thousands of moving objects in real time on typical personal computers and game consoles.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Where most of the objects involved are fixed, as is typical of video games, a priori methods using precomputation can be used to speed up execution.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Pruning is also desirable here, both *n*-body pruning and pairwise pruning, but the algorithms must take time and the types of motions used in the underlying physical system into consideration.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] When it comes to the exact pairwise collision detection, this is highly trajectory dependent, and one almost has to use a numerical root-finding algorithm to compute the instant of impact.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] At any point in time, the two triangles can be checked for intersection using the twenty planes previously mentioned.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] If $P(u,v,w)$ is the plane going through points $u,v,w$ in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ then there are twenty planes $P(v_{i}(t),v_{j}(t),v_{k}(t))$ to track.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Each plane needs to be tracked against three vertices, this gives sixty values to track.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Using a root finder on these sixty functions produces the exact collision times for the two given triangles and the two given trajectory.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] If the trajectories of the vertices are assumed to be linear polynomials in t then the final sixty functions are in fact cubic polynomials, and in this exceptional case, it is possible to locate the exact collision time using the formula for the roots of the cubic.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Some numerical analysts suggest that using the formula for the roots of the cubic is not as numerically stable as using a root finder for polynomials.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] A triangle mesh object is commonly used in 3D body modeling.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Normally the collision function is a triangle to triangle intercept or a bounding shape associated with the mesh.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] A triangle centroid is a center of mass location such that it would balance on a pencil tip.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The simulation need only add a centroid dimension to the physics parameters.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Given centroid points in both object and target it is possible to define the line segment connecting these two points.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The position vector of the centroid of a triangle is the average of the position vectors of its vertices.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Here the length/distance of the segment is an adjustable "hit" criteria size of segment.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] As the objects approach the length decreases to the threshold value.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] A triangle sphere becomes the effective geometry test.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] A sphere centered at the centroid can be sized to encompass all the triangle's vertices.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Physical simulators differ in the way they react on a collision.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Some use the softness of the material to calculate a force, which will resolve the collision in the following time steps like it is in reality.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] This is very CPU intensive for low softness materials.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Some simulators estimate the time of collision by linear interpolation, roll back the simulation, and calculate the collision by the more abstract methods of conservation laws.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Some iterate the linear interpolation (Newton's method) to calculate the time of collision with a much higher precision than the rest of the simulation.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Collision detection utilizes time coherence to allow even finer time steps without much increasing CPU demand, such as in air traffic control.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] After an inelastic collision, special states of sliding and resting can occur and, for example, the Open Dynamics Engine uses constraints to simulate them.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Constraints avoid inertia and thus instability.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Implementation of rest by means of a scene graph avoids drift.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In other words, physical simulators usually function one of two ways: where the collision is detected *a posteriori* (after the collision occurs) or *a priori* (before the collision occurs).
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In addition to the *a posteriori* and *a priori* distinction, almost all modern collision detection algorithms are broken into a hierarchy of algorithms.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Often the terms "discrete" and "continuous" are used rather than *a posteriori* and *a priori*.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In the *a posteriori* case, the physical simulation is advanced by a small step, then checked to see if any objects are intersecting or visibly considered intersecting.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] At each simulation step, a list of all intersecting bodies is created, and the positions and trajectories of these objects are "fixed" to account for the collision.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] This method is called *a posteriori* because it typically misses the actual instant of collision, and only catches the collision after it has actually happened.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In the *a priori* methods, there is a collision detection algorithm which will be able to predict very precisely the trajectories of the physical bodies.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The instants of collision are calculated with high precision, and the physical bodies never actually interpenetrate.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] This is called *a priori* because the collision detection algorithm calculates the instants of collision before it updates the configuration of the physical bodies.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The main benefits of the *a posteriori* methods are as follows.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In this case, the collision detection algorithm need not be aware of the myriad of physical variables; a simple list of physical bodies is fed to the algorithm, and the program returns a list of intersecting bodies.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The collision detection algorithm doesn't need to understand friction, elastic collisions, or worse, nonelastic collisions and deformable bodies.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In addition, the *a posteriori* algorithms are in effect one dimension simpler than the *a priori* algorithms.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] An *a priori* algorithm must deal with the time variable, which is absent from the *a posteriori* problem.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] On the other hand, *a posteriori* algorithms cause problems in the "fixing" step, where intersections (which aren't physically correct) need to be corrected.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Moreover, if the discrete step is too large, the collision could go undetected, resulting in an object which passes through another if it is sufficiently fast or small.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The benefits of the *a priori* algorithms are increased fidelity and stability.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] It is difficult (but not completely impossible) to separate the physical simulation from the collision detection algorithm.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] However, in all but the simplest cases, the problem of determining ahead of time when two bodies will collide (given some initial data) has no closed form solution—a numerical root finder is usually involved.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Some objects are in *resting contact*, that is, in collision, but neither bouncing off, nor interpenetrating, such as a vase resting on a table.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In all cases, resting contact requires special treatment: If two objects collide (*a posteriori*) or slide (*a priori*) and their relative motion is below a threshold, friction becomes stiction and both objects are arranged in the same branch of the scene graph.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Video games have to split their very limited computing time between several tasks.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Despite this resource limit, and the use of relatively primitive collision detection algorithms, programmers have been able to create believable, if inexact, systems for use in games.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] For a long time, video games had a very limited number of objects to treat, and so checking all pairs was not a problem.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In two-dimensional games, in some cases, the hardware was able to efficiently detect and report overlapping pixels between sprites on the screen.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In other cases, simply tiling the screen and binding each *sprite* into the tiles it overlaps provides sufficient pruning, and for pairwise checks, bounding rectangles or circles called hitboxes are used and deemed sufficiently accurate.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Three-dimensional games have used spatial partitioning methods for n -body pruning, and for a long time used one or a few spheres per actual 3D object for pairwise checks.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Exact checks are very rare, except in games attempting to simulate reality closely.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Even then, exact checks are not necessarily used in all cases.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Because games do not need to mimic actual physics, stability is not as much of an issue.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Almost all games use *a posteriori* collision detection, and collisions are often resolved using very simple rules.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] For instance, if a character becomes embedded in a wall, they might be simply moved back to their last known good location.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Some games will calculate the distance the character can move before getting embedded into a wall, and only allow them to move that far.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In many cases for video games, approximating the characters by a point is sufficient for the purpose of collision detection with the environment.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In this case, binary space partitioning trees provide a viable, efficient and simple algorithm for checking if a point is embedded in the scenery or not.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Such a data structure can also be used to handle "resting position" situation gracefully when a character is running along the ground.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Collisions between characters, and collisions with projectiles and hazards, are treated separately.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] A robust simulator is one that will react to any input in a reasonable way.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] For instance, imagining a high speed racecar video game, it is conceivable that the cars would advance a substantial distance along the race track from one simulation step to the next.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] If there is a shallow obstacle on the track (such as a brick wall), it is not entirely unlikely that the car will completely leap over it, and this is very undesirable.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] These are the hallmarks of a failing collision detection and physical simulation system.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] *Big Rigs: Over the Road Racing* is an infamous example of a game with a failing or possibly missing collision detection system.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] A **hitbox** is an invisible shape commonly used in video games for real-time collision detection; it is a type of bounding box.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] It is often a rectangle (in 2D games) or cuboid (in 3D) that is attached to and follows a point on a visible object (such as a model or a sprite).
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Circular or spheroidial shapes are also common, though they are still most often called "boxes".
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] It is common for animated objects to have hitboxes attached to each moving part to ensure accuracy during motion.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Hitboxes are used to detect "one-way" collisions such as a character being hit by a punch or a bullet.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] They are unsuitable for the detection of collisions with feedback (e.g. bumping into a wall) due to the difficulty experienced by both humans and AI in managing a hitbox's ever-changing locations; these sorts of collisions are typically handled with much simpler axis-aligned bounding boxes instead.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] Players may use the term "hitbox" to refer to these types of interactions regardless.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] A **hurtbox** is a hitbox used to detect incoming sources of damage.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] In this context, the term *hitbox* is typically reserved for those which deal damage.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] For example, an attack may only land if the hitbox around an attacker's punch connects with one of the opponent's hurtboxes on their body, while opposing hitboxes colliding may result in the players trading or cancelling blows, and opposing hurtboxes do not interact with each other.
[src:bullet-physics/collision-detection] The term is not standardized across the industry; some games reverse their definitions of *hitbox* and *hurtbox*, while others only use "hitbox" for both sides.
[src:bullet-physics/gilbert-johnson-keerthi-distance-algorithm] The **Gilbert–Johnson–Keerthi distance algorithm** is a method of determining the minimum distance between two convex sets, first published by Elmer G.
[src:bullet-physics/gilbert-johnson-keerthi-distance-algorithm] "Enhanced GJK" algorithms use edge information to speed up the algorithm by following edges when looking for the next simplex.
[src:bullet-physics/gilbert-johnson-keerthi-distance-algorithm] This improves performance substantially for polytopes with large numbers of vertices.
[src:bullet-physics/gilbert-johnson-keerthi-distance-algorithm] GJK makes use of Johnson's distance sub algorithm, which computes in the general case the point of a tetrahedron closest to the origin, but is known to suffer from numerical robustness problems.
[src:bullet-physics/gilbert-johnson-keerthi-distance-algorithm] GJK algorithms are often used incrementally in simulation systems and video games.
[src:bullet-physics/gilbert-johnson-keerthi-distance-algorithm] In this mode, the final simplex from a previous solution is used as the initial guess in the next iteration, or "frame".
[src:bullet-physics/gilbert-johnson-keerthi-distance-algorithm] If the positions in the new frame are close to those in the old frame, the algorithm will converge in one or two iterations.
[src:bullet-physics/gilbert-johnson-keerthi-distance-algorithm] This yields collision detection systems which operate in near-constant time.
[src:bullet-physics/gilbert-johnson-keerthi-distance-algorithm] The algorithm's stability, speed, and small storage footprint make it popular for realtime collision detection, especially in physics engines for video games.
[src:bullet-physics/gilbert-johnson-keerthi-distance-algorithm] The simplices handled by NearestSimplex may each be any simplex sub-space of **R***n*.
[src:bullet-physics/gilbert-johnson-keerthi-distance-algorithm] For example in 3D, they may be a point, a line segment, a triangle, or a tetrahedron; each defined by 1, 2, 3, or 4 points respectively.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] In geometry, the **Minkowski sum** of two subsets A and B of a Euclidean space is the set of the points whose position vectors form the sumset of the position vectors of A and B.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] The Minkowski sum depends on the choice of an origin in the Euclidean space.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] As a change of origin amounts to translate the Minkowski sum, the Minkowski sum is defined up to a translation, and its shape and orientation are well defined.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] The **Minkowski difference** (also *Minkowski subtraction*, *Minkowski decomposition*, or *geometric difference*) is the corresponding inverse, where ${\textstyle (A-B)}$ produces a set that could be summed with *B* to recover *A*.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] This is defined as the complement of the Minkowski sum of the complement of *A* with the reflection of *B* about the origin.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] This definition allows a symmetrical relationship between the Minkowski sum and difference.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Note that alternately taking the sum and difference with *B* is not necessarily equivalent.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] The sum can fill gaps which the difference may not re-open, and the difference can erase small islands which the sum cannot recreate from nothing.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] In 2D image processing the Minkowski sum and difference are known as dilation and erosion.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] An alternative definition of the Minkowski difference is sometimes used for computing intersection of convex shapes.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] This is not equivalent to the previous definition, and is not an inverse of the sum operation.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Instead it replaces the vector addition of the Minkowski sum with a vector subtraction.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] If the two convex shapes intersect, the resulting set will contain the origin.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] The concept is named for Hermann Minkowski.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] which comprises the vertices of a hexagon and its center.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] For another example, consider the Minkowski sums of open or closed balls in the field ${\textstyle \mathbb {K} ,}$ which is either the real numbers ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} }$ or complex numbers ${\textstyle \mathbb {C} }$ .
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] The Minkowski sum of a closed ball and an open ball is an open ball.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] More generally, the Minkowski sum of an open subset with *any* other set will be an open subset.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] This shows that the Minkowski sum of two closed sets is not necessarily a closed set.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] However, the Minkowski sum of two closed subsets will be a closed subset if at least one of these sets is also a compact subset.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] In mathematical terminology, the operations of Minkowski summation and of forming convex hulls are commuting operations.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] for every ${\textstyle \mu ,\lambda \geq 0}$ .
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Conversely, if this "distributive property" holds for all non-negative real numbers, ${\textstyle \mu }$ and ${\textstyle \lambda }$ , then the set is convex.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Minkowski sums act linearly on the perimeter of two-dimensional convex bodies: the perimeter of the sum equals the sum of perimeters.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Additionally, if ${\textstyle K}$ is (the interior of) a curve of constant width, then the Minkowski sum of ${\textstyle K}$ and of its 180° rotation is a disk.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] These two facts can be combined to give a short proof of Barbier's theorem on the perimeter of curves of constant width.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Minkowski addition plays a central role in mathematical morphology.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] It arises in the brush-and-stroke paradigm of 2D computer graphics (with various uses, notably by Donald E.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Knuth in Metafont), and as the solid sweep operation of 3D computer graphics.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] It has also been shown to be closely connected to the Earth mover's distance, and by extension, optimal transport.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Minkowski sums are used in motion planning of an object among obstacles.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] They are used for the computation of the configuration space, which is the set of all admissible positions of the object.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] In numerical control machining, the programming of the NC tool exploits the fact that the Minkowski sum of the cutting piece with its trajectory gives the shape of the cut in the material.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] In OpenSCAD Minkowski sums are used to outline a shape with another shape creating a composite of both shapes.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Minkowski sums are also frequently used in aggregation theory when individual objects to be aggregated are characterized via sets.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Minkowski sums, specifically Minkowski differences, are often used alongside GJK algorithms to compute collision detection for convex hulls in physics engines.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] For two convex polygons *P* and *Q* in the plane with *m* and *n* vertices, their Minkowski sum is a convex polygon with at most *m* + *n* vertices and may be computed in time O(*m* + *n*) by a very simple procedure, which may be informally described as follows.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Assume that the edges of a polygon are given and the direction, say, counterclockwise, along the polygon boundary.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Then it is easily seen that these edges of the convex polygon are ordered by polar angle.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Let us merge the ordered sequences of the directed edges from *P* and *Q* into a single ordered sequence *S*.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Imagine that these edges are solid arrows which can be moved freely while keeping them parallel to their original direction.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] Assemble these arrows in the order of the sequence *S* by attaching the tail of the next arrow to the head of the previous arrow.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] It turns out that the resulting polygonal chain will in fact be a convex polygon which is the Minkowski sum of *P* and *Q*.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] If one polygon is convex and another one is not, the complexity of their Minkowski sum is O(*nm*).
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] If both of them are nonconvex, their Minkowski sum complexity is O((*mn*)2).
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] There is also a notion of the **essential Minkowski sum** +e of two subsets of Euclidean space.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] where *μ* denotes the *n*-dimensional Lebesgue measure.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] where "ess sup" denotes the essential supremum.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] By the Minkowski inequality, the function *hK+pL* is again positive homogeneous and convex and hence the support function of a compact convex set.
[src:bullet-physics/minkowski-addition] This definition is fundamental in the *L**p* Brunn-Minkowski theory.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] A **physics engine** is computer software that provides an approximate simulation of certain physical systems, typically classical dynamics, including rigid body dynamics (including collision detection), soft body dynamics, and fluid dynamics.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] It is of use in the domains of computer graphics, video games and film (CGI).
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Their main uses are in video games (typically as middleware), in which case the simulations are in real-time.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] The term is sometimes used more generally to describe any software system for simulating physical phenomena, such as high-performance scientific simulation.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] There are generally two classes of physics engines: real-time and high-precision.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] High-precision physics engines require more processing power to calculate very precise physics and are usually used by scientists and prerendered computer animation, such as movies.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Real-time physics engines—as used in video games and other forms of interactive computing—use simplified calculations and decreased accuracy to compute in time for the game to respond at an appropriate rate for game play.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] A physics engine is essentially a big calculator that does mathematics needed to simulate physics.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] One of the first general purpose computers, ENIAC, was used as a very simple type of physics engine.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] It was used to design ballistics tables to help the United States military estimate where artillery shells of various mass would land when fired at varying angles and gunpowder charges, also accounting for drift caused by wind.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] The results were calculated a single time only, and were tabulated into printed tables handed out to the artillery commanders.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Physics engines have been commonly used on supercomputers since the 1980s to perform computational fluid dynamics modeling, where particles are assigned force vectors that are combined to show circulation.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Due to the requirements of speed and high precision, special computer processors known as vector processors were developed to accelerate the calculations.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] The techniques can be used to model weather patterns in weather forecasting, wind tunnel data for designing air- and watercraft or motor vehicles including racecars, and thermal cooling of computer processors for improving heat sinks.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] As with many calculation-laden processes in computing, the accuracy of the simulation is related to the resolution of the simulation and the precision of the calculations; small fluctuations not modeled in the simulation can drastically change the predicted results.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Tire manufacturers use physics simulations to examine how new tire tread types will perform under wet and dry conditions, using new tire materials of varying flexibility and under different levels of weight loading.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] The simulations optimize tire operations, material selection, costs, and enhance time efficiency.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] In most computer games, speed of the processors and gameplay are more important than accuracy of simulation.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] This leads to designs for physics engines that produce results in real-time but that replicate real world physics only for simple cases and typically with some approximation.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] More often than not, the simulation is geared towards providing a "perceptually correct" approximation rather than a real simulation.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] However some game engines, such as Source, use physics in puzzles or in combat situations.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] This requires more accurate physics so that, for example, the momentum of an object can knock over an obstacle or lift a sinking object.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Physically-based character animation in the past only used rigid body dynamics because they are faster and easier to calculate, but modern games and movies are starting to use soft body physics.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Soft body physics are also used for particle effects, liquids and cloth.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Some form of limited fluid dynamics simulation is sometimes provided to simulate water and other liquids as well as the flow of fire and explosions through the air.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Objects in games interact with the player, the environment, and each other.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Typically, most 3D objects in games are represented by two separate meshes or shapes.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] One of these meshes is the highly complex and detailed shape visible to the player in the game, such as a vase with elegant curved and looping handles.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] For purpose of speed, a second, simplified invisible mesh is used to represent the object to the physics engine so that the physics engine treats the example vase as a simple cylinder.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] It would thus be impossible to insert a rod or fire a projectile through the handle holes on the vase, because the physics engine model is based on the cylinder and is unaware of the handles.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] The simplified mesh used for physics processing is often referred to as the collision geometry.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] This may be a bounding box, sphere, or convex hull.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Engines that use bounding boxes or bounding spheres as the final shape for collision detection are considered extremely simple.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Generally a bounding box is used for broad phase collision detection to narrow down the number of possible collisions before costly mesh on mesh collision detection is done in the narrow phase of collision detection.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Another aspect of precision in discrete collision detection involves the framerate, or the number of moments in time per second when physics is calculated.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Each frame is treated as separate from all other frames, and the space between frames is not calculated.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] A low framerate and a small fast-moving object causes a situation where the object does not move smoothly through space but instead seems to teleport from one point in space to the next as each frame is calculated.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Projectiles moving at sufficiently high speeds will miss targets, if the target is small enough to fit in the gap between the calculated frames of the fast moving projectile.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Various techniques are used to overcome this flaw, such as *Second Life*'s representation of projectiles as arrows with invisible trailing tails longer than the gap in frames to collide with any object that might fit between the calculated frames.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] By contrast, continuous collision detection such as in Bullet or Havok does not suffer this problem.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] An alternative to using bounding box-based rigid body physics systems is to use a finite element-based system.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] In such a system, a 3-dimensional, volumetric tessellation is created of the 3D object.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] The tessellation results in a number of finite elements which represent aspects of the object's physical properties such as toughness, plasticity, and volume preservation.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Once constructed, the finite elements are used by a solver to model the stress within the 3D object.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] The stress can be used to drive fracture, deformation and other physical effects with a high degree of realism and uniqueness.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] As the number of modeled elements is increased, the engine's ability to model physical behavior increases.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] The visual representation of the 3D object is altered by the finite element system through the use of a deformation shader run on the CPU or GPU.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Finite Element-based systems had been impractical for use in games due to the performance overhead and the lack of tools to create finite element representations out of 3D art objects.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] James O'Brien as a part of his PhD thesis.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] In the real world, physics is always active.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] There is a constant Brownian motion jitter to all particles in our universe as the forces push back and forth against each other.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] For a game physics engine, such constant active precision is unnecessarily wasting the limited CPU power, which can cause problems such as decreased framerate.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Thus, games may put objects to "sleep" by disabling the computation of physics on objects that have not moved a particular distance within a certain amount of time.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] For example, in the 3D virtual world Second Life, if an object is resting on the floor and the object does not move beyond a minimal distance in about two seconds, then the physics calculations are disabled for the object and it becomes frozen in place.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] The object remains frozen until physics processing reactivates for the object after collision occurs with some other active physical object.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Physics engines for video games typically have two core components, a collision detection/collision response system, and the dynamics simulation component responsible for solving the forces affecting the simulated objects.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Modern physics engines may also contain fluid simulations, animation control systems and asset integration tools.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Finally, hybrid methods are possible that combine aspects of the above paradigms.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] A primary limit of physics engine realism is the approximated result of the constraint resolutions and collision result due to the slow convergence of algorithms.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Collision detection computed at a too low frequency can result in objects passing through each other and then being repelled with an abnormal correction force.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] On the other hand, approximated results of reaction force is due to the slow convergence of typical Projected Gauss Seidel solver resulting in abnormal bouncing.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Any type of free-moving compound physics object can demonstrate this problem, but it is especially prone to affecting chain links under high tension, and wheeled objects with actively physical bearing surfaces.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Higher precision reduces the positional/force errors, but at the cost of needing greater CPU power for the calculations.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] A physics processing unit (PPU) is a dedicated microprocessor designed to handle the calculations of physics, especially in the physics engine of video games.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Examples of calculations involving a PPU might include rigid body dynamics, soft body dynamics, collision detection, fluid dynamics, hair and clothing simulation, finite element analysis, and fracturing of objects.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] The idea is that specialized processors offload time-consuming tasks from a computer's CPU, much like how a GPU performs graphics operations in the main CPU's place.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] The term was coined by Ageia's marketing to describe their PhysX chip to consumers.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Several other technologies in the CPU-GPU spectrum have some features in common with it, although Ageia's solution was the only complete one designed, marketed, supported, and placed within a system *exclusively* as a PPU.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] Hardware acceleration for physics processing is now usually provided by graphics processing units that support more general computation, a concept known as general-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU).
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] AMD and NVIDIA provide support for rigid body dynamics computations on their latest graphics cards.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] NVIDIA's GeForce 8 series supports a GPU-based Newtonian physics acceleration technology named *Quantum Effects Technology*.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] NVIDIA provides an SDK Toolkit for CUDA (Compute Unified Device Architecture) technology that offers both a low and high-level API to the GPU.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] For their GPUs, AMD offers a similar SDK, called Close to Metal (CTM), which provides a thin hardware interface.
[src:bullet-physics/physics-engine] PhysX is an example of a physics engine that can use GPGPU based hardware acceleration when it is available.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In classical mechanics, **rigid body dynamics** studies the movement of systems of interconnected bodies under the action of external forces.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Along with statics, it forms the field of **rigid body mechanics**.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The assumption that the bodies are *rigid* (i.e. they do not deform under the action of applied forces) simplifies analysis, by reducing the parameters that describe the configuration of the system to the translation and rotation of body-fixed frames.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This excludes bodies that display fluid, highly elastic, and plastic behavior.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of a rigid body system is described by the laws of kinematics and by the application of Newton's second law (kinetics) or their derivative form, Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution of these equations of motion provides a description of the position, the motion and the acceleration of the individual components of the system, and overall the system itself, as a function of time.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The formulation and solution of rigid body dynamics is an important tool in the computer simulation of mechanical systems.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of particles moves parallel to a fixed plane, the system is said to be constrained to planar movement.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, Newton's laws (kinetics) for a rigid system of N particles, P*i*, *i*=1,...,*N*, simplify because there is no movement in the *k* direction.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where **r**i denotes the planar trajectory of each particle.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] For systems that are constrained to planar movement, the angular velocity and angular acceleration vectors are directed along **k** perpendicular to the plane of movement, which simplifies this acceleration equation.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {e} _{i}=0}$ and ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {t} _{i}=\mathbf {k} }$ is the unit vector perpendicular to the plane for all of the particles Pi.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where M is the total mass and *I***C** is the moment of inertia about an axis perpendicular to the movement of the rigid system and through the center of mass.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Several methods to describe orientations of a rigid body in three dimensions have been developed.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] They are summarized in the following sections.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The first attempt to represent an orientation is attributed to Leonhard Euler.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The values of these three rotations are called Euler angles.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Commonly, $\psi$ is used to denote precession, $\theta$ nutation, and $\phi$ intrinsic rotation.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] These are three angles, also known as yaw, pitch and roll, Navigation angles and Cardan angles.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Mathematically they constitute a set of six possibilities inside the twelve possible sets of Euler angles, the ordering being the one best used for describing the orientation of a vehicle such as an airplane.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In aerospace engineering they are usually referred to as Euler angles.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Euler also realized that the composition of two rotations is equivalent to a single rotation about a different fixed axis (Euler's rotation theorem).
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, the composition of the former three angles has to be equal to only one rotation, whose axis was complicated to calculate until matrices were developed.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Based on this fact he introduced a vectorial way to describe any rotation, with a vector on the rotation axis and module equal to the value of the angle.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, any orientation can be represented by a rotation vector (also called Euler vector) that leads to it from the reference frame.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, the rotation vector is commonly called orientation vector, or attitude vector.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] A similar method, called axis-angle representation, describes a rotation or orientation using a unit vector aligned with the rotation axis, and a separate value to indicate the angle (see figure).
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] With the introduction of matrices the Euler theorems were rewritten.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The rotations were described by orthogonal matrices referred to as rotation matrices or direction cosine matrices.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, a rotation matrix is commonly called orientation matrix, or attitude matrix.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The above-mentioned Euler vector is the eigenvector of a rotation matrix (a rotation matrix has a unique real eigenvalue).
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The product of two rotation matrices is the composition of rotations.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, as before, the orientation can be given as the rotation from the initial frame to achieve the frame that we want to describe.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The configuration space of a non-symmetrical object in *n*-dimensional space is SO(*n*) × **R***n*.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Orientation may be visualized by attaching a basis of tangent vectors to an object.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The direction in which each vector points determines its orientation.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Another way to describe rotations is using rotation quaternions, also called versors.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] They are equivalent to rotation matrices and rotation vectors.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] With respect to rotation vectors, they can be more easily converted to and from matrices.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent orientations, rotation quaternions are typically called orientation quaternions or attitude quaternions.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] To consider rigid body dynamics in three-dimensional space, Newton's second law must be extended to define the relationship between the movement of a rigid body and the system of forces and torques that act on it.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The extension of Newton's second law to rigid bodies is achieved by considering a rigid system of particles.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of *N* particles, Pi, i=1,...,*N*, are assembled into a rigid body, then Newton's second law can be applied to each of the particles in the body.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] An important simplification to these force equations is obtained by introducing the resultant force and torque that acts on the rigid system.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This resultant force and torque is obtained by choosing one of the particles in the system as a reference point, **R**, where each of the external forces are applied with the addition of an associated torque.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The resultant force **F** and torque **T** are given by the formulas, $\mathbf {F} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}\mathbf {F} _{i},\quad \mathbf {T} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}(\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )\times \mathbf {F} _{i},$ where **R**i is the vector that defines the position of particle Pi.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The mass properties of the rigid body are represented by its center of mass and inertia matrix.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] then it is known as the center of mass of the system.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the column vector **R**i − **R**; $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is its transpose, and $\mathbf {I}$ is the 3 by 3 identity matrix.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the scalar product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself, while $\mathbf {S} _{i}\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is the tensor product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Using the center of mass and inertia matrix, the force and torque equations for a single rigid body take the form $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a} ,\quad \mathbf {T} =[I_{R}]\alpha +\omega \times [I_{R}]\omega ,$ and are known as Newton's second law of motion for a rigid body.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of an interconnected system of rigid bodies, *B**i*, *j* = 1, ..., *M*, is formulated by isolating each rigid body and introducing the interaction forces.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Newton's formulation yields 6*M* equations that define the dynamics of a system of *M* rigid bodies.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] A rotating object, whether under the influence of torques or not, may exhibit the behaviours of precession and nutation.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution to this equation when there is no applied torque is discussed in the articles Euler's equation of motion and Poinsot's ellipsoid.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] It follows from Euler's equation that a torque **τ** applied perpendicular to the axis of rotation, and therefore perpendicular to **L**, results in a rotation about an axis perpendicular to both **τ** and **L**.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Precession can be demonstrated by placing a spinning top with its axis horizontal and supported loosely (frictionless toward precession) at one end.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Instead of falling, as might be expected, the top appears to defy gravity by remaining with its axis horizontal, when the other end of the axis is left unsupported and the free end of the axis slowly describes a circle in a horizontal plane, the resulting precession turning.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This effect is explained by the above equations.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The torque on the top is supplied by a couple of forces: gravity acting downward on the device's centre of mass, and an equal force acting upward to support one end of the device.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Under a constant torque of magnitude *τ*, the speed of precession *Ω*P is inversely proportional to *L*, the magnitude of its angular momentum: $\tau ={\mathit {\Omega }}_{\mathrm {P} }L\sin \theta ,$ where *θ* is the angle between the vectors **Ω**P and **L**.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, if the top's spin slows down (for example, due to friction), its angular momentum decreases and so the rate of precession increases.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This continues until the device is unable to rotate fast enough to support its own weight, when it stops precessing and falls off its support, mostly because friction against precession cause another precession that goes to cause the fall.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] By convention, these three vectors – torque, spin, and precession – are all oriented with respect to each other according to the right-hand rule.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] An alternate formulation of rigid body dynamics that has a number of convenient features is obtained by considering the virtual work of forces acting on a rigid body.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The virtual work of forces acting at various points on a single rigid body can be calculated using the velocities of their point of application and the resultant force and torque.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The trajectories of **R***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n* are defined by the movement of the rigid body.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The velocity of the points **R***i* along their trajectories are $\mathbf {V} _{i}={\boldsymbol {\omega }}\times (\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where **ω** is the angular velocity vector of the body.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] is known as the generalized force associated with the virtual displacement δq.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] It is useful to note that conservative forces such as gravity and spring forces are derivable from a potential function *V*(*q*1, ..., *q**n*), known as a potential energy.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The equations of motion for a mechanical system of rigid bodies can be determined using D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The principle of virtual work is used to study the static equilibrium of a system of rigid bodies; however, by introducing acceleration terms in Newton's laws this approach is generalized to define dynamic equilibrium.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The static equilibrium of a mechanical system rigid bodies is defined by the condition that the virtual work of the applied forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This is known as the *principle of virtual work.* This is equivalent to the requirement that the generalized forces for any virtual displacement are zero, that is *Q**i*=0.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Let a mechanical system be constructed from n rigid bodies, B*i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, and let the resultant of the applied forces on each body be the force-torque pairs, **F***i* and **T***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Notice that these applied forces do not include the reaction forces where the bodies are connected.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Finally, assume that the velocity **V***i* and angular velocities ***ω****i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, for each rigid body, are defined by a single generalized coordinate q.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Such a system of rigid bodies is said to have one degree of freedom.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] These m equations define the static equilibrium of the system of rigid bodies.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Consider a single rigid body which moves under the action of a resultant force **F** and torque **T**, with one degree of freedom defined by the generalized coordinate *q*.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work states that a system of rigid bodies is in dynamic equilibrium when the virtual work of the sum of the applied forces and the inertial forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, dynamic equilibrium of a system of n rigid bodies with m generalized coordinates requires that $\delta W=\left(Q_{1}+Q_{1}^{*}\right)\delta q_{1}+\dots +\left(Q_{m}+Q_{m}^{*}\right)\delta q_{m}=0,$ for any set of virtual displacements *δq**j*.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, introduce the Lagrangian, *L* = *T* − *V*, so these equations of motion become ${\frac {d}{dt}}{\frac {\partial L}{\partial {\dot {q}}_{j}}}-{\frac {\partial L}{\partial q_{j}}}=0\quad j=1,\ldots ,m.$ These are known as Lagrange's equations of motion.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The linear and angular momentum of a rigid system of particles is formulated by measuring the position and velocity of the particles relative to the center of mass.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Let the system of particles Pi, *i* = 1, ..., *n* be located at the coordinates **r***i* and velocities **v***i*.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] To specialize these formulas to a rigid body, assume the particles are rigidly connected to each other so Pi, i=1,...,n are located by the coordinates **r**i and velocities **v**i.
[src:bullet-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Select a reference point **R** and compute the relative position and velocity vectors, $\mathbf {r} _{i}=(\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {R} ,\quad \mathbf {v} _{i}=\omega \times (\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where ω is the angular velocity of the system.
